### Single-command C Builds

The examples below are validated with gcc / clang style command lines.
Compile the generated runtime and your application together:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 machine.c app.c -lm -o app
```

Equivalent explicit gcc / clang forms are:

```bash
gcc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 machine.c app.c -lm -o app
clang -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 machine.c app.c -lm -o app
```

For a no-heap build, define the same profile symbol for the generated runtime
and every consumer that includes `machine.h`:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -DPYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 machine.c app.c -lm -o app
```

A separate object build is also valid:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -c machine.c -o machine.o
cc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -c app.c -o app.o
cc machine.o app.o -lm -o app
```

On Windows, use the equivalent library or DLL flags for your compiler toolchain
and do not force-link the POSIX math library `m`.

### CMake Integration

A minimal static-library integration can look like this:

```cmake
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.5)
project(generated_machine_app C)

add_library(machine STATIC machine.c)
target_include_directories(machine PUBLIC ${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR})
set_target_properties(
    machine
    PROPERTIES
    C_STANDARD 99
    C_STANDARD_REQUIRED YES
    C_EXTENSIONS NO
)

if(NOT WIN32)
    target_link_libraries(machine PUBLIC m)
endif()

add_executable(app app.c)
target_link_libraries(app PRIVATE machine)
```

For a no-heap library that is consumed by other targets, propagate the macro as
part of the public interface:

```cmake
target_compile_definitions(machine PUBLIC PYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP)
```

If `machine.c` is compiled into an interface-style wrapper, use
`INTERFACE PYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP` on the wrapper target. A `PRIVATE`
definition is only safe when `machine.c` and all consumer source files that
include `machine.h` are compiled in the same final target and therefore see the
same macro.

### Single-command C++ Poll Wrapper Builds

Compile the C poll core as C99, then compile `machine.cpp` and your C++ application
as C++98. The wrapper is designed to work without exceptions, RTTI, STL
containers, or default heap allocation.

```bash
gcc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c machine.c -o machine.o
g++ -std=c++98 -fno-exceptions -fno-rtti -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c machine.cpp -o machine_cpp.o
g++ -std=c++98 -fno-exceptions -fno-rtti -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c app.cpp -o app.o
g++ machine.o machine_cpp.o app.o -lm -o app
```

The equivalent Clang / Clang++ form is:

```bash
clang -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c machine.c -o machine.o
clang++ -std=c++98 -fno-exceptions -fno-rtti -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c machine.cpp -o machine_cpp.o
clang++ -std=c++98 -fno-exceptions -fno-rtti -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c app.cpp -o app.o
clang++ machine.o machine_cpp.o app.o -lm -o app
```

A no-heap C++ poll-wrapper build uses the same profile macro for the C poll core,
`machine.cpp`, and every C++ source that includes `machine.hpp`:

```bash
gcc -std=c99 -DPYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c machine.c -o machine.o
g++ -std=c++98 -DPYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP -fno-exceptions -fno-rtti -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c machine.cpp -o machine_cpp.o
g++ -std=c++98 -DPYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP -fno-exceptions -fno-rtti -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 -c app.cpp -o app.o
g++ machine.o machine_cpp.o app.o -lm -o app
```

On Windows, keep the same source split but use your compiler's equivalent C99,
C++98, RTTI, exception, library, and DLL flags; do not add `-lm` for MSVC-style
linkers.

