### Native Toolchain Evidence

The repository-level native toolchain matrix builds representative generated
`c`, `c_poll`, `cpp`, and `cpp_poll` artifacts through pytest with the same
shared semantic fixture corpus used by the simulator and template-alignment
tests. Public profiles cover
hosted GCC / Clang optimization levels, 32-bit Linux, AArch64 with QEMU,
AppleClang, Windows MinGW / MSVC / clang-cl, sanitizer runs, compile-only ARM
bare-metal checks, and report-only static analysis such as `cppcheck` and
`clang-tidy`.

Those profiles are an engineering compatibility baseline, not a certification
claim. Treat them as reproducible evidence that the generated C and C++ public
APIs and shared semantics survive common compiler families and build modes. Safety
standards, coding-rule sign-off, board support packages, linker scripts, and
project-specific warning policies remain the responsibility of the downstream
integration process.

When a native matrix job fails, inspect the uploaded `result.json`,
`commands.json`, command logs, generated files, and harness files. Runnable
profiles also include `observations.jsonl`; compile-only and analyze-only
profiles intentionally do not produce runtime observations.

### Boundary Notes

- The no-heap profile only removes generated heap allocation helpers. It is not
  a strict freestanding guarantee; the generated runtime may still use standard
  headers such as `<math.h>`, `<string.h>`, or `<stdio.h>`.
- This generated runtime is not a claim of MISRA, AUTOSAR, DO-178C, IEC 61508,
  or ISO 26262 certification readiness.
- Binary layout, endian conversion, and cross-device persistence of variable
  snapshots are outside this public contract.

### Linkage and Visibility

- `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_API` is the generated symbol-visibility macro
  used by all public functions.
- Define `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_BUILD_SHARED` when building the
  generated runtime itself as a Windows DLL.
- Define `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_USE_SHARED` when consuming that DLL
  from external code on Windows.
- `machine.h` wraps only the public API declarations in `extern "C"` when
  included from C++.
- Public layout structs, hook typedefs, and event-check typedefs stay usable
  from both C and C++.
- In generated integer fields, `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}Int` is the
  public signed 64-bit type alias chosen to stay valid in both C99 and C++98+.

