## Performance Advice

- Treat the generated runtime as reusable stateful infrastructure: initialize
  once, cycle many times, and avoid unnecessary create/destroy churn.
- Keep abstract-hook registration sparse on critical paths; installed hooks
  introduce extra callback overhead.
- Event-check callbacks should be lightweight and read-only. Do not mutate
  persistent machine variables from event-check callbacks.
- Use `machine.h` as the stable public contract. Do not mutate runtime-owned
  internal fields such as `stack`, `stack_size`, `hooks`, `event_checks`, or
  `last_error` directly.
- Build production binaries with optimization enabled, for example `-O2` or
  `-O3`, and usually `-DNDEBUG`.
- If your toolchain supports it and your build policy allows it, LTO can help
  further: for example `-flto`.
- Prefer hot start when restoring from a known checkpoint, because it avoids
  reconstructing that checkpoint externally through many normal cycles.

## Compatibility Notes

- The generated runtime targets C99 and C++98 or later.
- The `c_poll` template keeps the same broad compatibility envelope as the
  built-in `c` runtime family while changing the event-input contract.
- Template regression checks are expected to compile representative generated
  machines with both a C compiler and a C++ compiler.
